    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Matching the Rating To Restaurant's Review</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Chef Joseph Sasso disputes M H Reed's July 2 review of Fish Cellar restaurant (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Regarding the July 2 review of the  The Fish Cellar, where I am chef:</p>
        <p>A review should coincide with the rating. M. H. Reed found one dish bland, using the words ''hospital kitchen'' to describe it, and then gave us a ''very good'' rating overall. That does not equate.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Regarding the July 2 review of the  The Fish Cellar, where I am chef:</p>
        <p>A review should coincide with the rating. M. H. Reed found one dish bland, using the words ''hospital kitchen'' to describe it, and then gave us a ''very good'' rating overall. That does not equate.</p>
        <p>Words should be chosen carefully.  If not, the review will confuse readers: ''Should we try this restaurant? I don't know, it got a 'very good' but it also mentioned something about hospital food.'' Hospital kitchen is not part of my vocabulary. You can critique my food but not degrade my work.</p>
        <p>JOSEPH SASSO  Mount Kisco</p>
      </block>
